Reference-contexts: Thus there may be too many solutions to the simplified problem to be useful. The Cartesian product representation [ Hubbe and Freuder, 1992 ] and interchangeability <ref> [ Freuder, 1991 ] </ref> techniques provide ways of working with compact representations of large sets of solutions. Interchangeability provides a principled approach to problem reformulation. Values are interchangeable if exchanging one for one another in any solution produces another solution. Interchangeable values form equivalence classes.
